<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">25051124</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2016</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>24</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2015</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>31</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1543-2920</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>27</Volume><Issue>1</Issue><PubDate><Year>2015</Year><Month>Feb</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Pediatric exercise science</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Pediatr Exerc Sci</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Effects of different doses of caffeine on anaerobic exercise in boys.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>50</StartPage><EndPage>56</EndPage><MedlinePgn>50-6</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1123/pes.2014-0032</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>This study investigated effects of low (1 mg&#xb7;kg-1), moderate (3 mg&#xb7;kg-1) and high (5 mg&#xb7;kg-1) doses of caffeine on anaerobic performance in boys. Twenty-six 8- to 10-year-old boys participated in a double-blind, crossover, counter-balanced study. Boys received in random order a placebo (PL) or anhydrous caffeine: 1 (CAF-1), 3 (CAF-3), or 5 (CAF-5) mg caffeine&#xb7;kg-1 body mass in cherry flavored Sprite. Sixty minutes following consumption boys performed a static handgrip test and then a 30-s Wingate test. Maximal grip strength (21.5 &#xb1; 4.9 &amp; 21.6 &#xb1; 4.7 vs. 20.4 &#xb1; 4.0 kg) was significantly higher in CAF-5 &amp; CAF-3 vs PL, respectively. Absolute and relative peak power (287 &#xb1; 72 vs 281 &#xb1; 69 W &amp; 8.0 &#xb1; 0.9 vs 7.8 &#xb1; 1.0 W&#xb7;kg-1) were significantly higher in CAF-3 vs PL, respectively. Mean power (153 &#xb1; 48 vs 146 &#xb1; 43 W) was significantly higher in CAF-5 vs PL, respectively. Peak Wingate HR was significantly higher (189 &#xb1; 8 vs 185 &#xb1; 9 beats&#xb7;min-1) in CAF-5 vs PL, respectively. These findings suggest that in boys CAF-1 did not affect performance. During the Wingate test CAF-3 resulted in higher peak power while CAF-5 increased mean power. The significant increase in peak HR following the Wingate test is likely related to greater mean power generated during CAF-5.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Turley</LastName><ForeName>Ken</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Dept. of Exercise and Sport Sciences, Harding University, Searcy, AR.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Eusse</LastName><ForeName>Paola A</ForeName><Initials>PA</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Thomas</LastName><ForeName>Myles M</ForeName><Initials>MM</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Townsend</LastName><ForeName>Jeremy R</ForeName><Initials>JR</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Morton</LastName><ForeName>Aaron B</ForeName><Initials>AB</Initials></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016449">Randomized Controlled Trial</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D013485">Research Support, Non-U.S. Gov't</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>Pediatr Exerc Sci</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>8909729</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>0899-8493</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><ChemicalList><Chemical><RegistryNumber>0</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D000697">Central Nervous System Stimulants</NameOfSubstance></Chemical><Chemical><RegistryNumber>3G6A5W338E</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D002110">Caffeine</NameOfSubstance></Chemical></ChemicalList><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><MeshHeadingList><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D015308" MajorTopicYN="N">Anaerobic Threshold</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI="Q000187" MajorTopicYN="Y">drug effects</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><Descri